The '''National Intelligence and Security Service''' ({{lang-ar|جهاز الأمن والمخابرات الوطني السوداني}}, ''Jihaaz Al Amn Al Watani Wal Mukhaabaraat'') is the [[intelligence service]] of the federal government of [[Sudan]]. The '''NISS''' is an incredibly powerful body, and has been granted extensive powers by the National Security Acts of 1999 and 2010 and has been referred to as a secret police organization.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/afr54/010/2010/en/ Amnesty International - Agents of Fear: The National Security Service in Sudan p.10]</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2012/10/03/an-idealist-on-death-row/|title=An Idealist on Death Row|work=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]|date=October 3, 2012|accessdate=February 21, 2015|last1=Caryl|first1=Christian|quote=...the Sudanese secret police — the notorious National Intelligence and Security Services (NISS)...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/has-the-arab-spring-now-spread-to-sudan-7893586.html|title=Has the Arab Spring now spread to Sudan?|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=June 28, 2012|accessdate=February 21, 2015|last1=Howden|first1=Daniel|quote=...and the hated secret police, the NISS.}}</ref>
It is widely accepted that in addition to its domestic operations, the NISS has operations and agents throughout the Middle East, North Africa and Western Europe. The secretive organisation's most well known operation is its massive intelligence network in [[Iraq]], which it was able to build by recruiting foreign fighters passing through [[Khartoum]] on their way to [[Iraq]].
From 2004 to 2009 the NISS was led by [[Salah Gosh]] until he was removed by [[Omar al-Bashir|President Al-Bashir]] and replaced with Mohammed Atta al-Moula, who the deputy director of the service who has led it ever since.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLE513341|title = Sudan president replaces intelligence chief|last = Wheeler|first = Skye|date = August 14, 2009|work = [[Reuters]]|access-date = January 5, 2016|via = }}</ref>
The NISS also operates the [[Rapid Support Forces]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article51298|title = Sudan’s RSF pledges to liberate rebel stronghold in South Kordofan|last = |first = |date = June 10, 2014|work = [[Sudan Tribune]]|access-date = January 5, 2016|via = |quote = The militia was activated and restructured again in August last year under the command of NISS}}</ref>
